         <div type="translation">
            <p>[ ] with heavy lamentation [ ] for three [mon]ths, who of God [ ] of June [ ] in
                    [ ] of June [ ]</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>In line 2, supplement “-ntis” with a name in the nominative or genitive. Another
                    possibility is the supplement “[---pare]nt{i}&lt;e&gt;s fili],” “his/her parents
                    for (their) son/daughter,” as “parentis” is a rather frequent alternative form
                    of the nominative plural “parentes.” In line 3, “dei g” could be restored “dei
                    g[ratiam---]” followed by a form of the verb accipio or recipio, “receive the
                    grace of God.” (Peter Lech)</p>
         </div>
